{
  "model": "llama-3.3-70b-versatile",
  "messages": [{
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Generate a Selenium Java test script 
-Verify login on a salesforce app.
-Use @BeforeMethod and @AfterMethod using testNg
-Use explicit waits instead of Thread.sleep().
-Validate both successful and unsuccessful login attempts.
-Use Only XPath for generating locators
-[MANDATORY] Generate only code and no other text
"
  }]
}

{
  "model": "llama-3.3-70b-versatile",
  "messages": [
         {
            "role": "system",
            "content": "Context: You are an testing expert in performance, security, usability testing.  Application caters to thousands of concurrent users. Persona: Senior performance test engineer with clear and precise instructions.  Output format:  use heading, and sub-heading and numbered lists for points under each group of test cases. Tone: strict"
        },

  {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Instructions:Create Non functional test cases with multiple test conditions  for the application supporting the use cases : Title: Update Debit Card Limits

As a bank customer,
I want to update the transaction limits on my debit card,
So that I can control my spending and enhance security based on my personal preferences.

Acceptance Criteria:

Limit Types:
The user should be able to update different types of limits, such as:

Daily purchase limit

Daily ATM withdrawal limit

Contactless payment limit (if applicable)

Validation:

The system should validate the new limit values to ensure they are within the allowed range set by the bank.

The user should receive an error message if they enter an invalid or unsupported limit.

Authentication:

The user must be authenticated (e.g., via login, OTP, or biometric) before updating the limits.

Confirmation:

After submitting the change, the user should receive a confirmation message indicating the new limits are in effect.

Optionally, a confirmation email or push notification should be sent.

Audit Trail:

The change should be logged in the system for auditing purposes and viewable in the user’s activity history."
  }],
  "temperature": 0.6
}
